post_text: The Ainsworth Girls Golf team had a successful first tournament at the O'Neill Invitational on Thursday, August 20th. Four of the five golfers carded personal record low scores, and the team finished in 8th place. Golfers setting a new PR were Josie G. (119), Ellie W. (132), Haley S. (149), and Libby S. (159). Allison T. was the fifth golfer rounding out the team. The team posted a score of 559, and has set the bar for continual improvement throughout the season. The girls golf team will have a busy week this week with two outings. They will be in action at the West Holt Scramble on Tuesday and the Ainsworth Invite will be on Thursday, August 27th starting at 9:30 AM.

post_text: We are very excited about the first day of school! This is a message for parents whose students ride the bus on the Johnstown or Long Pine Routes. Please recall we will be screening students for symptoms before boarding the bus each morning. We encourage parents to be 5-10 minutes early to your pick up point and be available in case there is an issue with your student and the driver or monitor needs to discuss the situation with you. We encourage parents to screen their children on their own before leaving for school. If your student is running a fever or other COVID related symptoms, please stay home and contact the office. Thank you!

5th & 6th Grade Supply List
Dear 5th and 6th graders,
Hello! We hope you have had a fun summer. Here is a suggested list of materials for
your core classes (language arts, math, science, and social studies):
Pencil bag - MUST be able to clip into a 3-ring binder
5 - 3 Ring Binders (1-inch thick) in the following colors:
● White - must have clear slip sleeve in the front
● Red (ELA)
● Blue (math)
● Green (science)
● Black (social studies)
2 Packages of loose-leaf paper
25 sharpened pencils
Colored pencils (12 count)
Package of red checking pens
4 pack of colored Highlighters (yellow, pink, green, blue) 4 glue sticks
2 black sharpies
Pair of scissors
1 subject spiral notebook
PE Shoes
*DO NOT bring pencil boxes or zippered binders such as "Trapper Keepers."
This list includes ALL the school supplies you will need for our classes. Remember, locker space is limited. We look forward to seeing you all in August!

-Mrs. Flynn, Mrs. Evans, Miss Lutter, and Mrs. Strelow

post_text:
It's Graduation Week! Emails were sent to last week from Mr. Dike (to senior parents) and Mrs. Welch (to seniors and senior parents) be sure you have checked your email. (We have several reports that these ended up going to spam folders for some reason!)

Key Reminders:

- Graduation practice will be held at 7:00 pm on Thursday in the gym, please be a few minutes early for screening.

- Parents, be looking for your student’s packet of tickets for Saturday. There will be a place on the back for the person who is using the ticket to PRINT their last name. This way we can collect the tickets and we will have the ability to let the health dept. know who actually used the ticket on graduation day.

- Please try to organize family guests in groups of 8 prior to getting to the door for screening. This will make seating in the gym much easier and more organized.

Thanks in advance for your help and we look forward to celebrating the Class of 2020!!!!

Mr. Steve Dike
7-12 Principal

post_text: The Ainsworth Community Schools Board of Education has been engaged with the Nebraska Association of School Boards in a review and revision of board policies. The new manual is available on the district website via a shared link. The shared link contains the table of contents for the new manual in addition to organized folders of the manual's specific sections. The board is conducting 1st and 2nd readings of the policy manual at the June and July regular board meetings respectively. After the 2nd reading at the July 13th meeting, the new policy manual will be in effect. Anyone who has questions, comments, or concerns related to the board policy manual should contact the office of the Superintendent. Thank you!

post_text: Awards for Art Students of the Year for 2020 were awarded to Raven Stewart and Ty Conroy. Both Raven and Ty have been in art during all four years of High School and 2 years of Middle School. Raven has mostly focused on drawing and painting, and Ty has focused on clay work. They have both won numerous awards during the past, and this year would have been no exception if we would have been able to attend the local Art shows. - Mrs. Adcock

post_text:
K-6 Parents/Guardians:

Under the new guidelines beginning June 1st, we are able to have face-to-face summer school, which is excellent news! We have made calls to some parents/guardians about students we would like to attend summer school, but are not full yet with our lists. If you would like your child(ren) to attend summer school, please EMAIL Mr. Childers @ cchilders@ainsworthschools.org. Slots will remain open until we reach our maximum number of 10 per grade level. Please only sign up if you are committing to come each day.

Summer school will run from June 8th until July 2nd (Monday through Thursday each week) for Kindergarten through Sixth grade students. Start time is 9:00am each day and students may be picked up at 11:30am.

If you sign up, you will receive an informational letter specifying the exact details.

Thanks,

Mr. Childers

post_text:
Students interested in taking the ACT: Here is a quick update. We are currently planning to give the National ACT on June 13th. (You have to be registered by tomorrow, May 8th, for the June test!) We will see what directives occur between now and then, and see if we will be allowed to test. We currently have 2 open spots for the general ACT and 2 open spots for the ACT with writing.

If we are not able to give the June National test, watch your email! I think they will reschedule you all to July 18th.

As far as the state junior ACT test, Nebraska Department of Education Statewide Assessment is still working with ACT, there is a possibility of having a state ACT test on a school day this fall. Nothing has been set up yet.

If you have ANY questions, please message Mrs. Schlueter.

post_text:
Parents: A few weeks ago 9-12 students were sent a youth survey by their seminar teacher. The survey is a joint effort with the Nebraska Community Foundation and the Brown County Community Foundation. We are aiming to seek the perspective of youth in our hometown. No student names or private information is used in the gathering of this information. Only aggregate results, not individual responses, will be shared in the final Nebraska Community Foundation report to the community of Ainsworth. The information students share will directly help with grantmaking decisions, where to spend money in the community, and identifying areas where there is potential for growth. Ultimately, these answers will help the Brown County Community Foundation Fund work toward building a community that our youth would be proud to return to.

*Only a third of our students completed the survey. Today the survey was sent again with another plea for them to please fill it out. Please check with your high school student and encourage them to complete the survey if they have not done so. Thank you!

Senior check-out will be held on Tuesday, May 12th from 8:15a.m-3:30p.m. Seniors - please check your email for a google doc that you will use to sign up for a 15-minute time slot. post_text: Next up in new staff introductions for the 20-21 school year is Alyssa Brennfoerder. Alyssa grew up in Edgar, a small town of 500 people in south central Nebraska. She began her college education in 2016 at Hastings College where she studied Elementary Education and K-12 Special Education. After graduation in May, she will get married in July before moving to Ainsworth. She looks forward to meeting the family of ACS as she begins her teaching career as one of our fourth grade teachers. Welcome to the ACS team, Alyssa! #ACSCARES

The school will begin providing breakfast and lunch meals, tomorrow, Wednesday, March 18th to any children in the community ages 1-18. To encourage social distancing we will run pickup locations at the Big A, East, and West Elementary entrances with 3-time slots that are alphabetical by last name. Please check the website and Facebook page for your time to pick up your meals or call the office. Meals will be provided on Mondays and Wednesdays. You will receive multiple meals at each pick-up time to correspond with the week.

Here is the schedule for picking up meals on Mondays and Wednesdays by last name:

11:15 to 11:30: A - C (Big A Doors) D - F (West Elem Doors) G - I (East Elem Doors)

11:30 to 11:45: J - K (Big A Doors) L - N (West Elem Doors) O - Q (East Elem Doors)

11:45 to Noon: R - T (Big A Doors) U - Z (West Elem Doors)

post_text:
Any student planning to take the National ACT test on April 4th: ACT has decided to reschedule the April students to the June or July test dates. Please watch your email or log into your account on act.org for more information in the coming days.

The NDE is suspending summative statewide assessment (NSCAS) for the 2019-2020 school year. This includes NSCAS – General, Alternate, and ACT. The NDE intends to pursue federal waivers for testing, accountability, and reporting requirements. The NDE is working with ACT to determine if all public high school juniors who would normally take the ACT as part of the statewide assessment may have the opportunity to take the ACT free-of-charge at a later date."

post_text: Dear ACS Community, after thoughtful consideration, it has been decided we will close school for an extended spring break for the following week, March 16-20. We met as a team of administration, staff, board representatives, and health professionals to arrive at this important decision. Our intent is to have the health and safety of our community at the forefront of all decisions related to the Coronavirus situation. Our #1 goal is to protect those in our community who are most vulnerable and encourage proper social distancing and isolation to accomplish that goal. By extending spring break, it will allow time for us to assess this very fluid situation, plan appropriately, and do the right thing in protecting our community. Please stay tuned for updates as we will update you on a frequent basis. School Teachers and Staff, please check your email for further information and directions related to the upcoming week. Thank you and please let us know if you have questions.

Dear ACS Community, we want to continue to provide you updates and information related to the Coronavirus or COVID-19. The Governor along with the Commissioner of Education provided more guidance to schools today regarding school closures. They recommend school going on as normal unless community cases of COVID-19 are confirmed. ACS will go on with school as planned at this time. I want to assure everyone that we are continually monitoring the situation and will work with local health, community, and state leaders to make decisions that are best for the communities and students we serve. Also, please note we are making preparations to work with students and staff in the event they must miss school for extended periods of time. Remember...ACS CARES.

The best source for updated and ongoing information is our North Central District Health Department's website. Please visit that site at:

https://ncdhdne.wordpress.com/

post_text: Great information from the North Central District Health Department.
shared_text:
North Central District Health Department
March 8 at 7:33 PM ·

As we work together in our communities to help prevent the spread of respiratory diseases, like COVID-19, there are a few things to remember:

1. If you are sick - stay home
2. If you feel you need to seek medial attention - call ahead so that healthcare teams can take precautionary preparedness measures prior to your arrival
3. Wash your hands for at least 20 seconds with warm water and soap
4. Avoid close contact with people who are sick
5. Avoid touching your eyes, nose, and mouth
6. Cover your cough or sneeze with a tissue, then throw the tissue in the trash.
7. Clean and disinfect frequently touched objects and surfaces using a regular household cleaning spray or wipe.

Great information from the North Central District Health Department.

North Central District Health Department
March 8 at 7:33 PM ·

As we work together in our communities to help prevent the spread of respiratory diseases, like COVID-19, there are a few things to remember:

1. If you are sick - stay home
2. If you feel you need to seek medial attention - call ahead so that healthcare teams can take precautionary preparedness measures prior to your arrival
3. Wash your hands for at least 20 seconds with warm water and soap
4. Avoid close contact with people who are sick
5. Avoid touching your eyes, nose, and mouth
6. Cover your cough or sneeze with a tissue, then throw the tissue in the trash.
7. Clean and disinfect frequently touched objects and surfaces using a regular household cleaning spray or wipe.

post_text: Saturday, February 15, students from Cody-Kilgore, Stanton, Sandhills, O’Neill and Ainsworth participated in the bi-annual production of Sing Around Nebraska. Eight sites hosted nearly 1000 4th, 5th and 6th grade singers over a period of three weeks in February. Sponsored by the Nebraska Choral Directors Association, students rehearsed for six weeks in preparation for the event. In most schools, students auditioned for the right to be part of the group. Under the direction of Erica Wiesler, Choral director from Gothenburg, the students presented an outstanding concert. Mrs. Nilson and Ms. Bejot feel fortunate to be able to host this incredible event, support excellence in choral music, and look forward to hosting again in two years.

post_text: Thirty-one students from Ainsworth High School recently traveled to Omaha, Ne to tour the Joslyn Museum. They view the special exhibition "Word & Image" which is the 1st handwritten illuminated Bible commissioned by a Benedictine Monastery since the 15th century. The Saint Johns' Bible incorporates contemporary imaging and events to connect traditional medieval craftsmanship with the 21st century. The students were able to view the finished pages as well as learn about the team of theologians, scientists, craftsmen, and others who created the illustrations, the calligraphy, and even the calfskin vellum these were written and painted on. They were also able to view traditional quill pens, bars of Chinese ink and they were able to handle a piece of vellum. The students also toured the permanent collection of the museum which includes American Western art, Native American Art as well as European Art.

post_text: On October 29th, the 8th grade students from Ainsworth Community Schools traveled to David City, NE to view art exhibits at the Bone Creek Museum of Agrarian Art. This museum focuses on art created to show rural and farming scenes. The first exhibit the students viewed was titled "Braceros: Melding History & Art". Sculptor Diana Le Marbe and painter Jeri Desrochers depict Mexican braceros workers who came to the United States between 1942-1964 to fill labor shortages in agriculture and the railroads caused by World War II. In all 28 states hired 4.5 million men during peak harvest and cultivation times to feed America. The second exhibit featured past rural scenes in Europe and the United States and featured a painting by Valentine artist David Dorsey. The students also toured the local history museum which is housed in an old train depot and they toured the Thorpe Opera House, which is listed on the National Register of Historic Places.

post_text: Recently the 7th grade class from Ainsworth Middle School traveled to Kearney, NE to view the exhibits at MONA (Museum of Nebraska Art). They were able to see exhibits by The Lundeens, a family dynasty of artists who are connected to Nebraska through George Lundeen who was born in Holdredge,NE. This exhibit was made up of bronze sculptures created by members of the Lundeen family. The students also viewed entitled "Nebraska Now: David Gracie, A Light that Casts No Shadow." These were paintings done in an extreme photo-realistic style. Also available for viewing was artwork by various artists in the exhibit "Optical Chronicle IV" based on author Henry M. Sayre's book "A World of Art". Students also saw works by various artists in the exhibit "Threaded", this displayed Nebraska related fiber arts spanning over 100 years and included quilts, wearables, and weavings, among other fiber based artworks. And of course the students were able to view MONA's permanent collection, which includes works by Robert Henri.

post_text: On Friday, October 18th the eighth grade class took a science field trip to Smith Falls State Park and Fort Niobrara National Wildlife Refuge. The purpose of this trip was to learn about and observe the five stratigraphic units found along the Niobrara River valley: the Rosebud Formation, the Valentine Formation, the Cap Rock Member of the Ash Hollow Formation, the Niobrara River Alluvium Terrace, and the Sand Hills. It was a first-time visit to Smith Falls (Nebraska's tallest waterfall) for eleven of our students. The day was filled with fresh air, sunshine, exercise, and learning!

post_text: On Tuesday, October 8th the eighth grade science classes enjoyed a presentation given by Amanda Hefner from the Nature Conservancy’s Niobrara Valley Preserve. Ms. Hefner taught us about the rock formations that can be seen in the Niobrara Valley, as well as some of the fossils that have been found in those rock layers. She also told us about the paleontologists who discovered fossils here including Morris Skinner and Bob Emry.

Ainsworth High School Art students traveled to Halsey, NE last week to attend the Teen Autumn Art Workshop. This was held at the 4-H Lodge at the Halsey National Forest!
The students had the choice of 4 workshops to participate in: Drawing in Nature, instructor Gibb Neal, Mandalas, instructor Kristi Kosmicki, Acrylic Landscape Painting with Beth Cole, and a Glass Blowing Demo by the Hasting College Mobile Glass Unit by Micheal Beahm.
This was the 7th Annual TAAW and Ainsworth has had the good fortune of being able to attend the last 3 years. Everyone who participated had an enjoyable experience and worked on their art skills!

Five students from Ainsworth Community Schools traveled to Hasting, NE on Wednesday, September 11 to participate in the Hastings College Mural Competition. There were approximately 34 schools attending with 200 students. The theme of this year's competition was "Memes". Each team was given an envelope that contained a meme typed on paper. Each team was to design a picture based on the meme they received. Ainsworth's meme was "When you thought someone was chill until you see them put ketchup on their pasta".
Graduate students from Hastings College Art program were the judges for this years competition.

post_text:
Pending board approval, dismissal will look differently this year. Grades K-4 will no longer be dismissed at 3:15p.m. The new dismissal time is 3:27p.m.

There will also be several changes regarding the flow of students and traffic at dismissal time.

· Students will now be loading and unloading the buses on the south side of the block near the middle school entrance. Bus monitors will escort bus kids to and from the buses at the new dismissal time.

· High school students who drive to school will now be required to enter and exit the parking lot through the alley.

· The above changes allow for parents to use the one way west of the school for pick up and drop off. Please be sure to use the one way correctly, to observe all parking and non-parking areas, and to watch for pedestrians in our busy crosswalks.

We will have staff outside assisting with direction before and after school for the first few days.

We are excited to announce a change in the way we rollout computers to students as we approach our 10th year of one to one computers for high school students.

Out of respect for everyone’s time, this year, computers will be rolled out to students on the first day of school versus an evening prior to the beginning of school as we had done in previous years.

You will be receiving paperwork in the mail, please review all of the information and once signed, the colored page can be dropped off at the school or sent with your student on the first day with the $35.00 lease fee if applicable.

The first day of school is quickly approaching and hopefully the change of the computer rollout will make the process more efficient for all involved.

Below is a short video which I would encourage you to watch. Topics in the video will be the types of information addressed with students on day one and throughout the year.

post_text: Today the sixth graders enjoyed a virtual field trip to a coral reef! We learned so much. Corals are made of thousands of tiny invertebrate animals called coral polyps. Each coral polyp is in a symbiotic relationship with algae that live inside the coral polyp. As the algae photosynthesize, they give the coral what it needs to live. Each tiny polyp secretes a hard outer skeleton of limestone. Over thousands of years, this builds up to form a reef. Some coral reefs are so large that they can be seen from space!

post_text:
On Thursday, May 2nd the sixth grade, seventh grade, and Mrs. Carr's seniors traveled to the fish hatchery in Valentine. While there, we released the trout that we have been raising since January. Students also enjoyed a tour of the hatchery, fishing, and an activity to model how scientists use macroinvertebrates to determine the biodiversity of a stream or pond.

We would like to thank the Nebraska Game and Parks and the Valentine State Fish Hatchery for hosting our fun field trip!

Youth Track & Field Classic is scheduled for this Saturday, May 4th at Ainsworth East City Park!

Registration begins at 9:30 a.m., field events begin at 10:00 a.m., and running events begin at 11:30 a.m. Students are limited to four events and ribbons will be handed out for the first six places in each event. Ainsworth Schools students do not need to pay the $5 registration fee. Students outside of the district are encouraged to participate, but will be required to pay the $5. If weather becomes a concern, tune in to KBRB for information.

Practice will be held this Thursday, May 2nd at 6:00pm at East City Park.
